## CONTEXT — What changed

The `openclaw-control` repo now ships a `Dockerfile` that builds an ephemeral
Ansible control runner image (`openclaw-control:ci`).  This adds a **third
execution context** for running Ansible against the VPS:

| Context | How |
|---|---|
| `LOCAL_SSH` | `ansible-playbook -i ansible/inventory ansible/site.yml --tags <tag>` |
| `LOCAL_DOCKER` | `docker run --rm -v "$PWD:/work" -v "$HOME/.ssh:/root/.ssh:ro" openclaw-control:ci -i ansible/inventory ansible/site.yml --tags <tag>` |
| `GITHUB_ACTIONS` | GitHub API workflow_dispatch → `link.yml` → ubuntu-latest runner → Ansible |

The Docker runner (`LOCAL_DOCKER`) is **ephemeral** — it runs one Ansible
command and exits.  The VPS is always the **remote target**, never the control
host.  No Ansible installation is needed on the operator's machine.

## Build command
```bash
docker build -t openclaw-control:ci .
```

## Run command (full status check example)
```bash
docker run --rm \
  -e ANSIBLE_HOST_KEY_CHECKING=False \
  -e ANSIBLE_SSH_ARGS="-F /dev/null" \
  -v "$PWD:/work" \
  -v "$HOME/.ssh:/root/.ssh:ro" \
  openclaw-control:ci \
  -i ansible/inventory ansible/site.yml --tags status-all
```

